 though, don&#39;t be surprised to see more wearables or even a tablet. Even if you didn&#39;t ask for either.</p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:11;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/samsung-will-focus-on-foldables-in-its-upcoming-july-unpacked-event-064922443.html"><strong>Continue reading.</strong></a></p><h2> <a data-i13n="cpos:12;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/openai-is-forming-a-team-to-rein-in-superintelligent-ai-214333388.html"><br>OpenAI is forming a team to rein in superintelligent AI</a></h2><h3> The announcement comes as governments debate how to regulate AI technologies.</h3><h3></h3><p> OpenAI is forming a dedicated team to manage the risks of superintelligent AI. A superintelligence is a hypothetical AI model smarter than even the most gifted and intelligent human, and it excels in multiple areas of expertise instead of one domain, like some previous-generation models. OpenAI 相信这样的模型可能会在本世纪末到来。</p><p> “Superintelligence will be the most impactful technology humanity has ever invented and could help us solve many of the world&#39;s most important problems,” the non-profit said. “But the vast power of superintelligence could also be very dangerous and could lead to the disempowerment of humanity or even human extinction.” I hope they recruit Sarah Connor.</p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:13;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/openai-is-forming-a-team-to-rein-in-superintelligent-ai-214333388.html"><strong>Continue reading.</strong></a></p><p></p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><h2> <a data-i13n="cpos:14;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/fisker-gives-the-best-look-yet-at-its-600-mile-range-ronin-ev-114048266.html">Fisker gives us a better look at its 600-mile range Ronin EV</a></h2><h3> It&#39;s set to be revealed in full on August 3rd.</h3><figure> <a href="https://www.engadget.com/fisker-gives-the-best-look-yet-at-its-600-mile-range-ronin-ev-114048266.html"><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/77d3f610-1be3-11ee-95e3-2c1defbd934f" style="height:454px;width:675px;" alt="TMA" data-uuid="346ee24f-eafb-3db5-b743-a21a166a8a16"></a><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit"> <a href="https://www.engadget.com/fisker-gives-the-best-look-yet-at-its-600-mile-range-ronin-ev-114048266.html">Fisker</a></div></figure><p> Fisker has given us another glimpse of the 600-mile range Ronin convertible EV and promised to unveil it in full on August 3rd. Like the original Fisker Karma, it&#39;s a low and swoopy four-door &quot;super GT&quot; sedan that will join its Ocean SUV. There&#39;s no word yet on price, but the company previously promised to keep it under $200,000. If that&#39;s out of your price range, Fisker is working on its most affordable EV yet, the four-door Pear, which should start at $29,900 before any incentives.</p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:15;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/fisker-gives-the-best-look-yet-at-its-600-mile-range-ronin-ev-114048266.html"><strong>Continue reading.</strong></a></p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/the-morning-after-metas-twitter-rival-threads-is-finally-here-111658179.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/the-morning-after-metas-twitter-rival-threads-is-finally-here-111658179.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> a2d72ad9-1f08-4af5-a159-452de408ad2f</guid><dc:creator> Mat Smith</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Thu, 06 Jul 2023 11:16:58 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1688638851</ingested><modified> 2023-07-06T10:20:57+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Mat Smith]]></category><media:content height="1280" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/dd9979c0-1b84-11ee-bfbf-1fec7fec1191" width="1920"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1280" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/dd9979c0-1b84-11ee-bfbf-1fec7fec1191" width="1920"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Meta]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[Meta's threads app looks similar to twitter,]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[threads app]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Threads gained 10 million new users in seven hours]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> Meta&#39;s Twitter rival Threads <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/metas-threads-app-is-here-to-challenge-twitter-230039730.html">just went live</a> and has already exceeded 10 million signups within the first seven hours, according to ( <a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://www.threads.net/t/CuWNIVrt78c">a Thread by</a> ) CEO Mark Zuckerberg. The app is now available globally ( <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/metas-twitter-rival-threads-wont-initially-launch-in-the-eu-090314803.html">except in Europe</a> ), with the rapid signup pace showing Meta&#39;s enormous ability to scale up compared to other Twitter rivals like <a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/bluesky-begins-offering-custom-domains-in-its-bid-to-remain-ad-free-071922355.html">Bluesky</a> — which still requires invite codes.</p><p> To, er, mark the occasion, Zuckerberg tweeted for the first time in over a decade with the classic Spider-Man standoff picture (showing that unlike Elon Musk, he actually knows how memes work). &quot;10 million signups in seven hours,&quot; he added on Threads. </p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><div id="505525f466854170916437a049b27e8e"><blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="zxx" dir="ltr"> <a href="https://t.co/MbMxUWiQgp">pic.twitter.com/MbMxUWiQgp</a></p> — Mark Zuckerberg (@finkd) <a href="https://twitter.com/finkd/status/1676747594460962817?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">July 6, 2023</a></blockquote></div><p> With Threads, Meta is taking on Twitter and <a data-i13n="cpos:5;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/twitter-alternatives-mastodon-223221883.html">alternatives</a> like Mastodon. It&#39;s under the purview of Instagram CEO Adam Mosseri, who is planning to make Threads compatible with ActivityPub. That&#39;s the source protocol that powers Mastodon and other decentralized services sometimes collectively referred to as the <a data-i13n="cpos:6;pos:1" href="https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2022/11/leaving-twitters-walled-garden">“Fediverse.”</a></p><p> Threads is strongly tied to Instagram and built on the same platform, giving Meta an effective way to advertise it. Any users who pre-ordered the app on iOS received a push notification when Threads went live, another move that no doubt boosted signups.</p><p> The site is not without early teething issues, though. The biggest complaint is the lack of a chronological, following-only feed, with users stuck with whatever the Threads algorithm decides to push their way. (&quot;95 percent of the posts I see are completely irrelevant to me,&quot; <a data-i13n="cpos:7;pos:1" href="https://www.threads.net/t/CuVzkVySv9F">complained one user</a> ). It also lacks post editing (which Facebook and Instagram both have), hashtags, account switching and more.</p><p> Mosseri has addressed all those issues, <a data-i13n="cpos:8;pos:1" href="https://www.threads.net/t/CuVlg88I84C/">posting on Threads</a> that a following-only feature is &quot;on the list.&quot; He said the same about <a data-i13n="cpos:9;pos:1" href="https://www.threads.net/t/CuVgdSOoGY9/">post editing</a> and <a data-i13n="cpos:10;pos:1" href="https://www.threads.net/t/CuVe8ViJ132/">account switching</a> , and added that hashtags will be tappable <a data-i13n="cpos:11;pos:1" href="https://www.threads.net/t/CuVfly1oARY/">&quot;in time</a> .&quot; </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/6c0c6970-1bd9-11ee-bb9f-0dd7ebc768da" style="height:317px;width:679px;" alt="Threads has already signed up 10 million users" data-uuid="6f29cea5-a59f-3487-8894-b0b429e665ad"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">恩杰特</div></figure><p>Another key problem for many users is the lack of a web version of Threads. Much like Instagram was for a long time, Threads is read-only on browsers, with posting limited to the iOS and Android apps (Mosseri has yet to address this). Finally, the design of Threads seems to be a love it or hate it affair, with some users finding the layout less intuitive than Twitter.</p><p> Verification remains another key talking point. Elon Musk famously <a data-i13n="cpos:12;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/twitter-starts-pulling-legacy-blue-verification-checkmarks-205010576.html">changed Twitter&#39;s system</a> so that only Twitter Blue subscribers would receive the blue check mark (or very notable public figures and news sites). That made the experience less enjoyable for many users, as it became difficult to tell who was an official athlete, celebrity, journalist, etc.</p><p> So far, only users verified on Instagram (and not Facebook) have received the blue badge on Threads. While Instagram verification is notoriously more difficult to get, it&#39;s largely held by influencers and creators. But Threads is positioned as a discussion site and will likely be focused on news (if it&#39;s to compete with Twitter), so it might make sense to allow Facebook verified users to also be verified on Threads — or create an all-new verification system.</p><p> In any case, it&#39;s still early days for Threads and the app will no doubt change substantially in the near future. It&#39;s clear that users have strong opinions — whether Meta listens to them or not will be an interesting story over the next few months.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/threads-gained-10-million-new-users-in-seven-hours-090838140.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/threads-gained-10-million-new-users-in-seven-hours-090838140.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> e8f1ebde-4bae-4644-b918-a57ebed74deb</guid><dc:creator> Steve Dent</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Thu, 06 Jul 2023 09:08:38 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1688634520</ingested><modified> 2023-07-06T09:08:45+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Media]]></category><category><![CDATA[Arts & Entertainment]]></category><category><![CDATA[Social & Online Media]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Steve Dent]]></category><media:content height="2609" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/5c6db290-1bce-11ee-9eff-8ce4a50b2bdb" width="3914"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="2609" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/5c6db290-1bce-11ee-9eff-8ce4a50b2bdb" width="3914"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[STEFANI REYNOLDS via Getty Images]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[TOPSHOT - This photo illustration created in Washington, DC, on July 5, 2023, shows Threads, an Instagram app, on the App Store, in front of the logos of Instagram and Threads. Facebook owner Meta's new Threads app, meant to compete with Twitter, was available for pre-order on mobile app stores on iPhone and Android operating systems on July 5, 2023. Listed as "Threads, an Instagram app," the new program should be available in the coming days, and is described on Apple's app store as "Instagram's text-based conversation app." (Photo by Stefani Reynolds / AFP) (Photo by STEFANI REYNOLDS/AFP via Getty Images)]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[TOPSHOT-US-TECH-TWITTER-FACEBOOK-META-SOCIAL]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Bluesky begins offering custom domains in its bid to remain ad-free]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> Jack Dorsey 支持的去中心化社交网络<a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/jack-dorsey-backed-bluesky-is-having-a-moment-133039184.html">Bluesky</a><a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://blueskyweb.xyz/blog/7-05-2023-namecheap">与 Namecheap 合作</a>推出了付费域名服务，作为用户验证身份的一种方式。在一篇讨论 Bluesky 可持续发展计划的<a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://blueskyweb.xyz/blog/7-05-2023-business-plan">帖子</a>中，该团队表示，当公司依赖广告时，“用户就成为产品”。由于 Bluesky 着手“建立一个用户可以拥有自己数据的协议”，因此它选择探索“其他货币化途径”。值得注意的是，这款社交应用最初是由 Twitter 资助的项目，但在埃隆·马斯克接手后就失去了与该网站的联系。</p><p>由于无法通过广告赚钱，因此团队考虑提供付费服务，从域名开始。用户已经可以设置自定义域名以与 Bluesky 一起使用，但他们必须首先通过域名注册商进行单独的流程。据称，这种集成将使他们能够在几分钟内完成此操作。他们只需登录自己的帐户，搜索用作句柄的域名，然后在 Bluesky 的界面中支付所有费用。对于没有集中式验证系统的 Twitter 竞争对手来说，使用域名是用户验证其身份的最佳方式。例如，美国参议员显然一直在使用 Senate.gov 域名来验证他们的身份。</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p>使用集成服务的用户将能够在 Bluesky 中管理其域设置和配置，并且可以将发送到其域的电子邮件转发到他们选择的地址。他们还可以选择将其域名重定向到 Bluesky 个人资料或任何他们想要的 URL。如果他们决定离开该平台或使用其他注册商，他们可以将域名转移出去。</p><p>根据 Bluesky 的公告，域集成只是该平台上可能提供的多项付费服务​​中的第一个。该公司表示正在探索“可以与用户捆绑在一起以提供更加无缝的体验”的其他服务。也就是说，Bluesky 仍处于内测阶段，感兴趣的人必须<a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1" href="https://bsky.app/">加入候补名单</a>才能进入。 </p><div id="e95cf09e09bc47009ccbecbfda4b9a97"><div style="left:0;width:100%;height:0;position:relative;padding-bottom:56.25%;"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/MGpJjq186bc?rel=0" style="top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;position:absolute;border:0;" allowfullscreen="" scrolling="no"></iframe></div></div><p></p>本文最初发表在 Engadget 上：https://www.engadget.com/bluesky-begins-offering-custom-domains-in-its-bid-to-remain-ad-free-071922355.html?src=rss]] >; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/bluesky-begins-offering-custom-domains-in-its-bid-to-remain-ad-free-071922355.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> c5f45aff-741a-4e4b-9cb0-53c4a7f3c3eb</guid><dc:creator>玛丽埃拉·穆恩</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Thu, 06 Jul 2023 07:19:22 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1688627962</ingested><modified> 2023-07-06T07:19:27+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Business]]></category><category><![CDATA[Internet & Networking Technology]]></category><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Mariella Moon]]></category><media:content height="4024" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/f4d944a0-19a2-11ee-9bfd-59714ec92889" width="6048"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="4024" medium="image" url=